Optimizers in Deep Learning:¶

An Overview of most common optimizers used in ML.

Different types of Optimizers¶

  • Gradient Descent
  • Stochastic Gradient Descent (SGD)
  • Mini-Batch Gradient Descent
  • Stochastic Gradient Descent (SGD)with Momentum
  • Adaptive Gradient Descent (AdaGrad)
    • Gradient Descent with learning rate tuning
  • RMS-Prop (Root Mean Square Propagation)
    • A special version of AdaGrad: Learning rate is an exponentially averaged of the gradients
    • Combination of AdaGrad & Momentum
  • AdaDelta
  • Adam(Adaptive Moment Estimation)
  • Nesterov Accelerated Gradient (NAG)

Gradient Descent¶

Definition of Gradient:¶

A gradient measures how much the output of a function changes if you change the inputs a little bit." Lex Fridman (MIT).

Gradient/Slope, $\boldsymbol{\nabla = \frac{Rise \,(\Delta Y)}{Run\,(\Delta X)}}$

  • It measures the changes in the errors with respect to a small changes in the loss function.\
  • It can easily undesrtand as the slope of a function.
  • If the slope is steep the model approaches to the minima quickly, if the slope is too low the model stop learning and remains at a steady point.
  • It is the partial derivative of the Objective Function/Loss Function

image source

$$\boldsymbol{\theta = \theta - \eta. \overbrace{\nabla_{\theta}J(\theta;x,y)}^\text{Backpropagation}}$$
  • $\boldsymbol{\theta}$ is a parameter (w,b, or activations). Here we only update a single parameter.
  • $\boldsymbol{\eta}$ is the learning rate
  • $\boldsymbol{\nabla}$ is Gradient of cost function $\boldsymbol{J}$
  • $\boldsymbol{J}$ is the Pbjective function that we are going to optimize (commonly known as loss or cost function)

Advantages:

  • Easy computation.
  • Easy to implement.
  • Easy to understand.

Disadvantages:

  • May trap at local minima.
  • Weights are changed after calculating the gradient on the whole dataset. So, if the dataset is too large then this may take years to converge to the minima.
  • Requires large memory to calculate the gradient on the whole dataset.

Learning rate:

  • Learning Rate is very important in Gardient Descent.
  • If the learning rate is too high, it may step over the global minima.
  • If the learning rate is too low, it may get stuck in the local minima.
  • Learning rate is a hyper parameter, sometimes maybe optimized by Cross- Validations.
